ive data gathered from an urban public library infrastructure, this historical case study demonstrates how public sphere communication shaped the infrastructure’s development over time, producing both changes and continuities across the case’s nine periods. Two new conceptual tools—circuits and decisions cycles—form the study’s research framework, and a new explanatory theory—RLCr, or "Releaser," theory—accounts for why the infrastructure developed as it did. Consideration of competing theories reveals that public sphere communication remains the best explanation for infrastructural development. This book’s meticulous historical narrative of the greater Pittsburgh case, supplemented by its groundbreaking theory and innovative mixed methods design, is of interest to practitioners, academics, and general readers alike.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aBibliothek. 4aPittsburgh, US. 4aÖffentlicher Raum. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Library & Information Science / General.2bisacsh  aPublic sphere, public libraries, Pittsburgh (US), historical methods.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Library and Information Science 2023 Englishz978311131915508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Library and Information Science 2023z9783111318233oZDB-23-DGB0 cEPUBz97831110141420 cprintz978311101225440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311101340440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111013404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783